Sukanya,

1) Unless you want to update something else, no.
2) Not in a negative way, may cause improvements.
3) Configuration file, as stated in the upgrade article

The WebServer.exe.config file is automatically retained in a Backup folder created under the Web folder of the installation directory. Any custom application settings contained in this file are kept as part of this upgrade process.


Do recommend to make a manual backup just in case.
4) In your case: Upgrade in place – Performs file content updates of jobs matching the Instant Solutions but does not change the Jobs tree structure
5) No and no, aside from ensuring your Web Service and AIC Service are running from and AD ACCOUNT WITH DB ACCESS, or you will not be able to access Published Reports/AIC

TextBody:
1) Unless you want to update something else, no.
2) Not in a negative way, may cause improvements.
3) Configuration file, as stated in the upgrade article

The WebServer.exe.config file is automatically retained in a Backup folder created under the Web folder of the installation directory. Any custom application settings contained in this file are kept as part of this upgrade process.


Do recommend to make a manual backup just in case.

1) Unless you want to update something else, no.
2) Not in a negative way, may cause improvements.
3) Configuration file, as stated in the upgrade article



The WebServer.exe.config file is automatically retained in a Backup folder created under the Web folder of the installation directory. Any custom application settings contained in this file are kept as part of this upgrade process.
